---

<Infographic
  title="Quantum teleportation"
  description="Quantum teleportation moves an unknown qubit's state from one location to another by consuming a shared Bell pair and sending two classical bits. No copy of the original state remains at the sender, consistent with no-cloning. This page covers the protocol, the resources it consumes, why it isn't faster than light, and its role as the link-layer 'send a qubit' primitive."
  references={[
    "bennett-prl-1993",
    "cacciapuoti-ieeetc-2020",
    "kozlowski-rfc9340",
    "kumar-ijndc-2025",
    "wootters-nature-1982",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="teleportation" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>Quantum teleportation</h1>
        <p>
          A qubit cannot be copied — the no-cloning theorem forbids any unitary that
          duplicates an unknown <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />. But a qubit's <em>state</em>
          can be moved from one place to another, by consuming a shared Bell pair and
          sending two classical bits over a classical channel. The state leaves the sender's
          qubit in the process — no copy of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> remains at the
          sender afterwards — and the destination ends up holding a different physical
          qubit in that same quantum state. This is <strong>quantum
          teleportation</strong> <SourceNote id="bennett-prl-1993" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          The network's job is to deliver Bell pairs; teleportation is what users do
          with them. Each qubit teleported consumes one Bell pair and two classical
          bits. In the entanglement-mediated architecture covered by 1G and 2G
          repeaters, this is the only way to move an unknown qubit between nodes —
          no-cloning forbids copying it, and any single photon carrying the state
          would be lost to channel attenuation long before reaching the far end. 3G
          repeaters take a different route: they send QEC-encoded photonic qubits
          directly down the channel and correct loss/operation errors at each hop,
          with no Bell pair or classical sideband involved. The repeaters page
          covers that contrast in detail.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section id="what" data-nav-section>
        <h2>What teleportation does</h2>
        <p>
          Alice has a qubit in some unknown state
          <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle = \\alpha|0\\rangle + \\beta|1\\rangle" />. She wants
          Bob to end up with a qubit in the same state. Teleportation does this with
          three ingredients:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>a <strong>pre-shared Bell pair</strong> — Alice holds one half, Bob the other;</li>
          <li>a <strong>joint measurement at Alice</strong> on her unknown qubit and her Bell half;</li>
          <li><strong>two classical bits</strong> sent to Bob, and a Pauli correction he applies to his Bell half.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Bob's qubit then carries <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />. Alice never measures
          <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> in a way that reveals it, never copies it, and
          never sends it down the fibre — none of which would work.
        </p>

        <Callout label="Why the naive approaches fail">
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Measure and send.</strong> Reading <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> in any
              basis collapses it; the outcome reveals only one bit's worth of statistics, not
              the continuous complex amplitudes <Math tex="\\alpha" /> and
              <Math tex="\\beta" />. The qubit is left in a basis state and the information
              needed to recreate <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> is gone.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Copy and ship.</strong> No-cloning forbids creating a second qubit in
              the same unknown state.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Send the qubit physically.</strong> A photon carrying
              <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> can travel through fibre, but no-cloning rules
              out optical amplification — and at long distances loss compounds without an
              amplification mechanism that preserves quantum state.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </Callout>
      </section>

      <section id="protocol" data-nav-section>
        <h2>The protocol</h2>
        <p>
          The starting resource is a Bell pair
          <Math tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle_{AB} = (|00\\rangle + |11\\rangle)/\\sqrt{2}" />
          shared between Alice and Bob — Alice holds qubit <Math tex="A" />, Bob holds
          qubit <Math tex="B" />. Alice additionally holds the qubit
          <Math tex="C" /> in the state <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> she wants to
          teleport. The protocol then proceeds in four steps:
        </p>

        <ol class="tp-steps">
          <li>
            <strong>Initial joint state.</strong> The three qubits together are
            <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle_C \\otimes |\\Phi^+\\rangle_{AB}" />. Re-expanding on
            <Math tex="C, A" /> in the Bell basis,
            <Math display tex="|\\psi\\rangle_C \\otimes |\\Phi^+\\rangle_{AB} = \\tfrac{1}{2}\\bigl( |\\Phi^+\\rangle_{CA} |\\psi\\rangle_B + |\\Phi^-\\rangle_{CA} Z|\\psi\\rangle_B + |\\Psi^+\\rangle_{CA} X|\\psi\\rangle_B + |\\Psi^-\\rangle_{CA} ZX|\\psi\\rangle_B \\bigr)." />
            The state of the three qubits hasn't changed — this is the same vector written
            in a different basis. But it now exposes that <Math tex="B" /> is correlated
            with <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> up to a Pauli operator, indexed by which
            Bell state <Math tex="C, A" /> sit in.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Bell-state measurement at Alice.</strong> Alice measures
            <Math tex="C" /> and <Math tex="A" /> jointly in the Bell basis. The
            measurement projects them onto one of the four Bell states with equal
            probability ¼ and yields two classical bits
            <Math tex="(a, b)" />.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Classical communication.</strong> Alice sends <Math tex="(a, b)" /> to
            Bob over a classical channel. At this point Bob's qubit is in
            <Math tex="P|\\psi\\rangle" /> — the right state up to a known Pauli operator
            <Math tex="P \\in \\{I, X, Z, ZX\\}" />.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Pauli correction at Bob.</strong> Bob applies <Math tex="X^b Z^a" />,
            which equals the inverse of <Math tex="P" />. His qubit is now in
            <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          The bit pattern <Math tex="(a, b)" /> tells Bob which Bell state Alice's BSM
          collapsed onto, and therefore which Pauli to apply:
        </p>

        <table class="tp-pauli-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>(a, b)</th><th>Bell outcome</th><th>State at Bob before correction</th><th>Pauli <Math tex="P^{-1}" /> to apply</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>(0, 0)</td><td><Math tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="I" /></td></tr>
            <tr><td>(0, 1)</td><td><Math tex="|\\Psi^+\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="X|\\psi\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="X" /></td></tr>
            <tr><td>(1, 0)</td><td><Math tex="|\\Phi^-\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="Z|\\psi\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="Z" /></td></tr>
            <tr><td>(1, 1)</td><td><Math tex="|\\Psi^-\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="ZX|\\psi\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="ZX" /></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <Callout label="Does Bob already have |ψ⟩ after Alice's measurement?">
          <p>
            Not quite. The moment Alice's BSM fires, Bob's qubit is in
            <Math tex="P|\\psi\\rangle" /> — one of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />,
            <Math tex="X|\\psi\\rangle" />, <Math tex="Z|\\psi\\rangle" />, or
            <Math tex="ZX|\\psi\\rangle" /> — and Bob doesn't yet know which. He cannot
            distinguish these four states from local measurements alone (his density
            matrix is <Math tex="\\tfrac{1}{2}\\mathbb{I}" /> regardless), so the qubit
            carries no usable information until the two bits arrive and he can apply
            <Math tex="P^{-1}" />. <em>Then</em> Bob holds <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />.
            Calling <Math tex="B" /> <q>the teleported qubit</q> before the correction is
            a shorthand — the state of the qubit at that moment is
            <Math tex="P|\\psi\\rangle" />, not <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />.
          </p>
        </Callout>

        <figure class="tp" id="tp-fig" data-tp>
          <svg viewBox="0 0 720 320" role="img"
               aria-label="Quantum teleportation protocol animation: top row shows C, A, B photons; Alice's BSM measures C and A, producing two classical bits that travel to Bob."
               data-tp-svg>
            <defs>
              <radialGradient id="tp-cloud-std" cx="0.5" cy="0.5" r="0.5">
                <stop offset="0%"   stop-color="var(--tp-teal)"   stop-opacity="0.95"/>
                <stop offset="40%"  stop-color="var(--tp-teal)"   stop-opacity="0.55"/>
                <stop offset="100%" stop-color="var(--tp-teal)"   stop-opacity="0"/>
              </radialGradient>
              <radialGradient id="tp-cloud-psi" cx="0.5" cy="0.5" r="0.5">
                <stop offset="0%"   stop-color="var(--tp-purple)" stop-opacity="0.95"/>
                <stop offset="40%"  stop-color="var(--tp-purple)" stop-opacity="0.55"/>
                <stop offset="100%" stop-color="var(--tp-purple)" stop-opacity="0"/>
              </radialGradient>
            </defs>

            {/* ─── Endpoint labels ───────────────────────────── */}
            <text x="160" y="22" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-label">Alice</text>
            <text x="560" y="22" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-label">Bob</text>

            <rect x="20"  y="32" width="280" height="280" rx="6"
                  fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <rect x="420" y="32" width="280" height="280" rx="6"
                  fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="1"/>

            {/* ─── Photon row (top): C left, A middle, B right ─────
                C and A on Alice's side, B on Bob's side. All aligned
                at y=100 so the entangled-pair line A↔B runs cleanly
                horizontal. */}

            {/* Letter labels above the photons. */}
            <text x="70"  y="70" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-slot-label">C</text>
            <text x="240" y="70" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-slot-label">A</text>
            <text x="560" y="70" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-slot-label">B</text>

            {/* Photons. Position is in `transform` so animations can
                move them along the diagonal into the BSM. */}
            <g data-tp-c transform="translate(70 100)">
              <circle r="16" fill="url(#tp-cloud-psi)"/>
            </g>
            <g data-tp-a transform="translate(240 100)">
              <circle r="16" fill="url(#tp-cloud-std)"/>
            </g>
            <g data-tp-b transform="translate(560 100)">
              <circle data-tp-b-cloud r="16" fill="url(#tp-cloud-std)"/>
            </g>

            {/* ─── Entangled-pair line A ↔ B (high-frequency wave) ─── */}
            <path data-tp-bellpair
                  d="M 0 0"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--tp-teal)" stroke-width="1.4"
                  opacity="0.9"/>

            {/* ─── BSM box (Alice, vertical-down layout) ─────────────
                C and A photons travel diagonally down into the box.
                Two bit-ports on the bottom emit (a, b) as the
                measurement fires. */}
            <g data-tp-bsm opacity="0">
              {/* Diagonal input beams from C and A photons to the
                  top edge of the BSM box. */}
              <line x1="70"  y1="116" x2="135" y2="180"
                    stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1"
                    stroke-dasharray="2,2"/>
              <line x1="240" y1="116" x2="185" y2="180"
                    stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1"
                    stroke-dasharray="2,2"/>
              {/* BSM module: a rounded rectangle, two top-edge ports
                  marked by small notch-circles, two bottom-edge ports. */}
              <rect x="100" y="180" width="120" height="56" rx="6"
                    fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--tp-teal)" stroke-width="1.8"/>
              <circle cx="135" cy="180" r="3" fill="var(--tp-teal)"/>
              <circle cx="185" cy="180" r="3" fill="var(--tp-teal)"/>
              <circle cx="140" cy="236" r="3" fill="var(--tp-teal)"/>
              <circle cx="180" cy="236" r="3" fill="var(--tp-teal)"/>
              {/* BSM label. */}
              <text x="160" y="206" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-bsm-title">BSM</text>
              {/* Bell-outcome ket below the title. */}
              <text data-tp-bell-out x="160" y="226" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-bell-out">|Φ⁺⟩</text>
              {/* Vertical output lines from bottom ports down to the
                  bit pair below. */}
              <line x1="140" y1="236" x2="140" y2="260"
                    stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1"
                    stroke-dasharray="2,2"/>
              <line x1="180" y1="236" x2="180" y2="260"
                    stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1"
                    stroke-dasharray="2,2"/>
            </g>

            {/* ─── Classical channel (horizontal, just below BSM) ─── */}
            <text x="360" y="252" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-channel">classical channel · 2 bits</text>
            <line x1="220" y1="276" x2="500" y2="276"
                  stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1"
                  stroke-dasharray="4,3" opacity="0.65"/>

            {/* ─── Bit pair (a, b) — sits under BSM, then slides right ── */}
            <g data-tp-bits opacity="0">
              <text data-tp-bits-text x="160" y="280" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-bit">(0, 0)</text>
            </g>

            {/* ─── Bob's correction (under B) ──────────────────── */}
            {/* P badge — small chip overlaid below B during phases 2-3. */}
            <g data-tp-bob-pauli opacity="0" transform="translate(560 138)">
              <rect x="-14" y="-10" width="28" height="20" rx="3"
                    fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--tp-purple)" stroke-width="1.4"/>
              <text data-tp-bob-pauli-text x="0" y="5" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-pauli-badge">P</text>
            </g>
            {/* P⁻¹ correction box — appears in phase 4. */}
            <g data-tp-corr-box opacity="0" transform="translate(560 200)">
              <rect x="-32" y="-14" width="64" height="28" rx="3"
                    fill="none" stroke="var(--tp-purple)" stroke-width="1.6"
                    stroke-dasharray="3,2"/>
              <text data-tp-corr-text x="0" y="5" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-action-label">P⁻¹</text>
            </g>
          </svg>

          <ol class="tp-step-list" data-tp-steps>
            <li data-tp-step="1"><strong>1.</strong> Alice has C; A and B are a shared Bell pair</li>
            <li data-tp-step="2"><strong>2.</strong> Alice performs BSM on C and A → bits (a, b)</li>
            <li data-tp-step="3"><strong>3.</strong> Bits travel to Bob; B holds P|ψ⟩</li>
            <li data-tp-step="4"><strong>4.</strong> Bob applies P⁻¹</li>
            <li data-tp-step="5"><strong>5.</strong> B now matches C</li>
          </ol>

          <figcaption>
            Top row: three photons. <strong>C</strong> (purple) is the qubit Alice wants
            to teleport; <strong>A</strong> and <strong>B</strong> (teal) are halves of
            a pre-shared Bell pair, drawn connected by a high-frequency wavy line.
            <strong>C</strong> and <strong>A</strong> drop diagonally into Alice's BSM
            box; the outcome ket appears inside and two classical bits emerge as
            <Math tex="(a, b)" /> below. At that same instant <strong>B</strong> turns
            purple with a <Math tex="P" /> badge — it's now <Math tex="P|\\psi\\rangle" />.
            The bits slide right along the classical channel; when they reach Bob he
            applies <Math tex="P^{-1}" />, the badge drops, and <strong>B</strong> ends
            up the same purple as <strong>C</strong>. The Bell pair is consumed.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section id="circuit" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Circuit diagram</h2>
        <p>
          As a quantum circuit, the protocol runs on three wires — Alice's input qubit
          <Math tex="C" />, Alice's half of the Bell pair <Math tex="A" />, and Bob's
          half <Math tex="B" /> — with time flowing left to right. The three conceptual
          stages are Bell-pair creation, the Bell-state measurement, and the Pauli
          correction <SourceNote id="cacciapuoti-ieeetc-2020" />.
        </p>

        <figure class="tp-circuit">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 760 280" role="img"
               aria-label="Teleportation circuit: Bell-pair creation, Bell-state measurement, and Pauli correction">

            {/* ─── Region labels (right side) ─────────────────── */}
            <text x="730" y="74" class="tp-c-region">Alice</text>
            <text x="730" y="134" class="tp-c-region">Alice</text>
            <text x="730" y="194" class="tp-c-region">Bob</text>

            {/* ─── Initial state labels (left) ─────────────────── */}
            <text x="40" y="76" text-anchor="end" class="tp-c-state">|ψ⟩</text>
            <text x="40" y="136" text-anchor="end" class="tp-c-state">|0⟩</text>
            <text x="40" y="196" text-anchor="end" class="tp-c-state">|0⟩</text>

            {/* ─── Quantum wires ───────────────────────────────── */}
            <line x1="50" y1="70"  x2="720" y2="70"  stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="50" y1="130" x2="720" y2="130" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="50" y1="190" x2="720" y2="190" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>

            {/* ─── Block 1: Bell-pair creation ─────────────────── */}
            <rect x="65" y="110" width="125" height="100" rx="4"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
            <text x="127" y="100" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-block">Bell-pair |Φ⁺⟩ creation</text>

            {/* H on Alice's |0⟩ (middle wire) */}
            <rect x="85" y="120" width="22" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <text x="96" y="135" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-gate">H</text>

            {/* CNOT: control middle, target bottom */}
            <line x1="155" y1="130" x2="155" y2="190" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <circle cx="155" cy="130" r="4" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <circle cx="155" cy="190" r="9"
                    fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="146" y1="190" x2="164" y2="190" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="155" y1="181" x2="155" y2="199" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>

            {/* ─── Block 2: Bell-state measurement (BSM) ──────── */}
            <rect x="225" y="50" width="160" height="100" rx="4"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
            <text x="305" y="42" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-block">Bell-state measurement</text>

            {/* CNOT: control top, target middle */}
            <line x1="245" y1="70" x2="245" y2="130" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <circle cx="245" cy="70" r="4" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <circle cx="245" cy="130" r="9"
                    fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="236" y1="130" x2="254" y2="130" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="245" y1="121" x2="245" y2="139" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>

            {/* H on top wire */}
            <rect x="280" y="60" width="22" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <text x="291" y="75" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-gate">H</text>

            {/* Measurement on top */}
            <rect x="335" y="60" width="32" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <path d="M 343 78 A 8 8 0 0 1 359 78" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <line x1="351" y1="78" x2="361" y2="64" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1"/>

            {/* Measurement on middle */}
            <rect x="335" y="120" width="32" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <path d="M 343 138 A 8 8 0 0 1 359 138" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <line x1="351" y1="138" x2="361" y2="124" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1"/>

            {/* ─── Classical wires (double lines) ──────────────── */}
            {/* Top measurement → Z gate (label "a") */}
            <path d="M 367 68 H 638 V 184" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
            <path d="M 367 72 H 642 V 184" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="0.8"/>

            {/* Middle measurement → X gate (label "b") */}
            <path d="M 367 128 H 568 V 184" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
            <path d="M 367 132 H 572 V 184" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="0.8"/>

            {/* Classical-bit labels on the wires */}
            <text x="500" y="62" class="tp-c-bit">a</text>
            <text x="465" y="122" class="tp-c-bit">b</text>

            {/* ─── Block 3: Pauli correction ──────────────────── */}
            <rect x="555" y="170" width="120" height="40" rx="4"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
            <text x="615" y="227" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-block">Pauli correction</text>

            {/* X^b */}
            <rect x="565" y="180" width="28" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <text x="579" y="195" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-gate">X<tspan baseline-shift="super" font-size="9">b</tspan></text>

            {/* Z^a */}
            <rect x="635" y="180" width="28" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <text x="649" y="195" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-gate">Z<tspan baseline-shift="super" font-size="9">a</tspan></text>

            {/* Final state label at right end of Bob's wire */}
            <text x="710" y="186" text-anchor="end" class="tp-c-state">|ψ⟩</text>

            {/* ─── Time arrow at bottom ───────────────────────── */}
            <line x1="50" y1="252" x2="720" y2="252" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="0.6"/>
            <polygon points="720,252 714,249 714,255" fill="var(--color-rule)"/>
            <text x="50" y="266" class="tp-c-time">time →</text>
          </svg>
          <figcaption>
            <strong>Bell-pair creation:</strong> a Hadamard on Alice's
            <Math tex="|0\\rangle" /> followed by a CNOT onto Bob's
            <Math tex="|0\\rangle" /> produces the Bell pair
            <Math tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle_{AB}" />.
            <strong>Bell-state measurement:</strong> a CNOT, a Hadamard, and two
            single-qubit measurements project Alice's <Math tex="C" /> and
            <Math tex="A" /> jointly onto a Bell state, yielding two classical bits —
            <em>a</em> from the <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> measurement, <em>b</em>
            from the Bell-half measurement. Double lines are the classical wires
            carrying those bits to Bob.
            <strong>Pauli correction:</strong> Bob applies <Math tex="X^b" /> followed
            by <Math tex="Z^a" /> to undo the Pauli operator the BSM outcome left on his
            qubit, completing the transfer of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> onto
            <Math tex="B" />.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section id="math" data-nav-section>
        <h2>No faster-than-light shortcut</h2>
        <Callout label="Why Alice can't cheat by reading her bits">
          <p>
            Before Alice's classical message arrives, Bob's qubit
            <Math tex="B" /> is in a uniform mixture of
            <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />, <Math tex="X|\\psi\\rangle" />,
            <Math tex="Z|\\psi\\rangle" />, and <Math tex="ZX|\\psi\\rangle" /> — its
            local density matrix is <Math tex="\\tfrac{1}{2}\\mathbb{I}" />, the maximally
            mixed state, regardless of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />. Bob's local
            statistics are independent of Alice's outcome, so he learns nothing about
            <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> from his half alone. Only when he receives the
            two bits and applies the matching correction does the qubit become useful.
            Teleportation is therefore compatible with relativity — no information
            crosses faster than the classical bits do.
          </p>
        </Callout>
      </section>

      <section id="ledger" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Resources and limits</h2>
        <p>
          Each teleported qubit consumes a fixed budget:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>1 Bell pair</strong>, consumed in Alice's BSM. The Bell pair is the
            quantum resource — getting it to both ends is the network's job
            (covered in the distribution and links subjects).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>2 classical bits</strong>, sent over a classical channel from Alice to
            Bob. The classical message is what makes teleportation no faster than light.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>The original <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> at Alice, gone.</strong>
            Alice's BSM projects <Math tex="C" /> and <Math tex="A" /> jointly onto a Bell
            state, leaving no copy of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> at Alice — consistent
            with no-cloning. In photonic BSM the <Math tex="C" /> and <Math tex="A" />
            photons are absorbed at the detectors; in matter implementations (trapped ions,
            NV centres) the qubits remain physically but are now in a known Bell state with
            each other. Either way, exactly one copy of the state exists in the protocol at
            any time <SourceNote id="wootters-nature-1982" />.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Two consequences follow from this resource ledger. First, teleportation
          degrades with the fidelity of the Bell pair: a noisy pair gives Bob a noisy
          copy of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />, and the cleaner the pair, the cleaner
          the teleported state — which is why distillation exists, to take noisy pairs
          and produce cleaner ones. Second, the protocol is one-shot per Bell pair;
          teleporting many qubits requires many Bell pairs, which is why
          entanglement-distribution rate (Bell pairs per second) is a headline network
          metric.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="role" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Network role</h2>
        <p>
          Teleportation sits at the boundary between the network and the application.
          The network promises one thing: deliver Bell pairs at adequate rate, fidelity,
          and reach. The application's "send a qubit" operation is implemented by
          teleportation on top of that promise. Other applications — entanglement-based
          QKD, blind quantum computing, distributed quantum computing — also consume
          delivered Bell pairs; teleportation is the simplest case of using
          one <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          Two related primitives, covered in their own subjects, share teleportation's
          BSM machinery:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Entanglement swapping</strong> uses a BSM at a relay station to
            extend a Bell pair across an extra hop, without any of the four end-to-end
            qubits ever interacting. Memory-based repeaters chain swaps to span long
            distances. <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>swapping</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Distillation</strong> applies local CNOTs and measurements at both
            ends of a noisy pair to trade two low-fidelity pairs for one higher-fidelity
            pair. <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>distillation</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </Stack>
  </Center>
</Infographic>

<script type="module" is:inline>
  // Teleportation animation. Visual storyline:
  //   1. Setup — Alice has C (purple cloud = |ψ⟩) and A (standard
  //      cloud, Bell half). Bob has B (standard cloud, Bell half).
  //      Entangled-wave connects A and B.
  //   2. BSM — BSM box wraps C and A. Bell outcome ket appears
  //      between them; bits (a, b) emerge below. At the same instant,
  //      B picks up a purple tint with a "P" badge — physically it's
  //      now in P|ψ⟩, even though Bob doesn't know which P.
  //   3. Classical send — (a, b) travels along the classical line.
  //   4. Correction — bits arrive at Bob; the P badge drops, B turns
  //      fully purple = |ψ⟩ on Bob.
  //   5. Hold final state, reset.
  //
  // No bar rotations: state equivalence is shown by cloud colour.
  // C and A do not disappear during BSM — they dim and the Bell-
  // outcome ket overlays them, reflecting the projection onto a
  // known Bell state rather than annihilation.
  const fig = document.querySelector("[data-tp]");
  if (fig) {
    const svg          = fig.querySelector("[data-tp-svg]");
    const photonC      = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-c]");
    const photonA      = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-a]");
    const photonB      = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-b]");
    const bCloud       = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-b-cloud]");
    const bellLine     = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-bellpair]");
    const bsmGlyph     = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-bsm]");
    const bellOut      = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-bell-out]");
    const bobPauli     = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-bob-pauli]");
    const bobPauliText = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-bob-pauli-text]");
    const corrBox      = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-corr-box]");
    const corrText     = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-corr-text]");
    const bitsGroup    = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-bits]");
    const bitsText     = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-bits-text]");
    const stepEls      = Array.from(fig.querySelectorAll("[data-tp-step]"));

    // Photon home positions (top row) and BSM entry points.
    const C_HOME = { x:  70, y: 100 };
    const A_HOME = { x: 240, y: 100 };
    const B_HOME = { x: 560, y: 100 };
    const C_BSM  = { x: 135, y: 180 };  // top-left BSM port
    const A_BSM  = { x: 185, y: 180 };  // top-right BSM port
    const BIT_X_START = 160;
    const BIT_X_END   = 560;

    // High-frequency sinewave from A's right edge to B's left edge.
    (function buildBellLine() {
      const x0 = A_HOME.x + 18, x1 = B_HOME.x - 18, y = 100;
      const lambda = 14, amp = 5;
      const n = Math.round((x1 - x0) / lambda);
      const step = (x1 - x0) / n;
      let d = `M ${x0} ${y} `;
      d += `q ${step/4} ${-amp*2} ${step/2} 0 `;
      for (let i = 1; i < n*2; i++) d += `t ${step/2} 0 `;
      bellLine.setAttribute("d", d);
    })();
    function setPos(g, x, y) { g.setAttribute("transform", `translate(${x} ${y})`); }

    // Bell outcome (a,b) → state ket, Pauli operator. Matches the
    // (a,b) → P table in the prose. Bob applies P⁻¹ which equals P
    // for I, X, Z (self-inverse) and equals XZ for ZX (up to sign).
    const OUTCOMES = [
      { a: 0, b: 0, ket: "|Φ⁺⟩", P: "I"  },
      { a: 0, b: 1, ket: "|Ψ⁺⟩", P: "X"  },
      { a: 1, b: 0, ket: "|Φ⁻⟩", P: "Z"  },
      { a: 1, b: 1, ket: "|Ψ⁻⟩", P: "ZX" },
    ];

    const reducedMotion = matchMedia("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)").matches;

    function setOpacity(el, op) { el.setAttribute("opacity", String(op)); }
    function highlightStep(n) {
      for (const el of stepEls) {
        el.classList.toggle("tp-step--active", Number(el.dataset.tpStep) === n);
      }
    }
    function setBitsX(x)     { bitsText.setAttribute("x", String(x)); }
    function setBobTint(p)   {
      // 0 = pure standard cloud (teal), 1 = pure purple. The standard
      // cloud sits beneath; we fade in the purple overlay on top.
      bobPauli.querySelector("circle").setAttribute("opacity", String(0.55 * p));
    }

    if (reducedMotion) {
      const o = OUTCOMES[1];
      bitsText.textContent = `(${o.a}, ${o.b})`;
      bellOut.textContent  = o.ket;
      setOpacity(bsmGlyph, 0.85);
      setOpacity(photonC, 0);
      setOpacity(photonA, 0);
      setOpacity(bellLine, 0.15);
      setOpacity(bitsGroup, 1);
      setBitsX(BIT_X_END);
      setOpacity(bobPauli, 0);
      bCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-psi)");
      setOpacity(corrBox, 1);
      highlightStep(5);
    } else {
      const T_SETUP = 1100;
      const T_BSM   = 1400;
      const T_SEND  = 1800;
      const T_CORR  = 1200;
      const T_HOLD  = 1100;
      const T_PAUSE = 300;
      const T_TOTAL = T_SETUP + T_BSM + T_SEND + T_CORR + T_HOLD + T_PAUSE;

      let cycleStart = 0;
      let outcome = OUTCOMES[0];

      const PULSE_DUR = 280;
      const flash = { CORR: 0 };
      const corrRect = corrBox.querySelector("rect");
      let firedBSM = false;
      let firedCorr = false;
      function pulse(side, now) { flash[side] = now + PULSE_DUR; }
      function updateBorders(now) {
        const remaining = flash.CORR - now;
        if (remaining > 0) {
          const t = remaining / PULSE_DUR;
          corrRect.setAttribute("stroke-width", String(1.6 + 2 * t));
        } else {
          corrRect.setAttribute("stroke-width", "1.6");
        }
      }
      function ease(t) {
        return t < 0.5 ? 4 * t * t * t : 1 - Math.pow(-2 * t + 2, 3) / 2;
      }

      function pickCycleParams() {
        outcome = OUTCOMES[Math.floor(Math.random() * 4)];
        bitsText.textContent      = `(${outcome.a}, ${outcome.b})`;
        bellOut.textContent       = outcome.ket;
        bobPauliText.textContent  = outcome.P;
        corrText.textContent      = outcome.P + "⁻¹";
        bCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-std)");
        setPos(photonC, C_HOME.x, C_HOME.y);
        setPos(photonA, A_HOME.x, A_HOME.y);
      }

      function frame(now) {
        const elapsed = now - cycleStart;

        if (elapsed < T_SETUP) {
          // Phase 1 — three photons in a row at the top; entangled
          // wave from A to B.
          highlightStep(1);
          setOpacity(photonC, 1);
          setOpacity(photonA, 1);
          setPos(photonC, C_HOME.x, C_HOME.y);
          setPos(photonA, A_HOME.x, A_HOME.y);
          setOpacity(bellLine, 0.9);
          setOpacity(bsmGlyph, 0);
          setOpacity(bobPauli, 0);
          setOpacity(corrBox, 0);
          setOpacity(bitsGroup, 0);
        } else if (elapsed < T_SETUP + T_BSM) {
          // Phase 2 — BSM box appears; C and A travel diagonally
          // into its top ports. Bell outcome emerges; bits appear
          // at the bottom of the BSM. B picks up purple tint + P.
          highlightStep(2);
          if (!firedBSM) firedBSM = true;
          const t = (elapsed - T_SETUP) / T_BSM;
          const e = ease(t);
          setOpacity(bsmGlyph, Math.min(1, e * 2));
          setOpacity(bellLine, 0.9 * (1 - 0.85 * e));
          // Photon C: home → C_BSM port (diagonal).
          setPos(photonC,
            C_HOME.x + (C_BSM.x - C_HOME.x) * e,
            C_HOME.y + (C_BSM.y - C_HOME.y) * e);
          setPos(photonA,
            A_HOME.x + (A_BSM.x - A_HOME.x) * e,
            A_HOME.y + (A_BSM.y - A_HOME.y) * e);
          // Photons disappear once they reach the BSM ports.
          setOpacity(photonC, Math.max(0, 1 - (e - 0.75) * 4));
          setOpacity(photonA, Math.max(0, 1 - (e - 0.75) * 4));
          // Bits appear under BSM in the last quarter of the phase.
          const bitO = Math.max(0, (e - 0.6) * 2.5);
          setOpacity(bitsGroup, bitO);
          setBitsX(BIT_X_START);
          // Bob simultaneously enters P|ψ⟩.
          if (e > 0.5) bCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-psi)");
          setOpacity(bobPauli, Math.max(0, (e - 0.35) * 1.6));
        } else if (elapsed < T_SETUP + T_BSM + T_SEND) {
          // Phase 3 — bits slide right along the classical channel.
          highlightStep(3);
          const t = (elapsed - T_SETUP - T_BSM) / T_SEND;
          setOpacity(photonC, 0);
          setOpacity(photonA, 0);
          setOpacity(bsmGlyph, 0.85);
          setOpacity(bellLine, 0.13);
          setOpacity(bitsGroup, 1);
          setBitsX(BIT_X_START + (BIT_X_END - BIT_X_START) * t);
          setOpacity(bobPauli, 1);
        } else if (elapsed < T_SETUP + T_BSM + T_SEND + T_CORR) {
          // Phase 4 — bits arrive at B, Bob applies P⁻¹, P drops.
          highlightStep(4);
          if (!firedCorr) { pulse("CORR", now); firedCorr = true; }
          const t = (elapsed - T_SETUP - T_BSM - T_SEND) / T_CORR;
          const e = ease(t);
          setOpacity(bitsGroup, 1 - e);
          setBitsX(BIT_X_END);
          setOpacity(corrBox, Math.min(1, e * 2));
          setOpacity(bobPauli, 1 - e);
        } else if (elapsed < T_TOTAL - T_PAUSE) {
          // Phase 5 — B fully purple, matches C's original colour.
          highlightStep(5);
          setOpacity(bsmGlyph, 0.4);
          setOpacity(bitsGroup, 0);
          setOpacity(corrBox, 1);
          setOpacity(bobPauli, 0);
        } else if (elapsed >= T_TOTAL) {
          cycleStart = now;
          firedBSM = false;
          firedCorr = false;
          pickCycleParams();
        }
        updateBorders(now);
        requestAnimationFrame(frame);
      }

      pickCycleParams();
      cycleStart = performance.now();
      requestAnimationFrame(frame);
    }
  }
</script>

